{
  "texts": [
    "Although imaging of removed organs and tissues can be performed for medical reasons, they are typically considered part of pathology.",
    "Other imaging techniques, such as electroencephalography (EEG), magnetoencephalography (MEG), and electrocardiography (ECG), are not primarily designed to produce images but can be considered forms of medical imaging in another medical instrumentation discipline.",
    "As of 2010, 5 billion medical imaging studies were conducted worldwide, with radiation exposure from medical imaging accounting for about 50% of total ionizing radiation exposure in the United States.",
    "Medical imaging equipment is manufactured using semiconductor industry technology, with annual shipments of medical imaging chips amounting to 46 million units and $1.1 billion.",
    "III.Precision Medicine with AI: The convergence of artificial intelligence (AI) and precision medicine promises to revolutionize health care."
  ]
}